nder the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]},{"name":"Owain","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Perhaps derived in the Roman period from the Latin name <i>Eugenius</i> (  see  <b>Eugene</b>   ); alternatively, possibly from an Old Celtic name meaning ‘born of Esos’. Esos (or Aesos) was a Celtic god known to have been the subject of a cult in ancient Gaul."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan ferch Owain of Abergavenny was born in 1354, in Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales, her father, Owain Ap Caradoc, was 52 and her mother, Lleucu Gwyn ferch Einion Sais, was 52. She married John Jenkin. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1354–":"1354–Surnud","1347–Female":"1347–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1302–1365":"1302–1365","1302–1320":"1302–1320","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1354":"1354","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1354–":"1354–Kuollut","1347–Female":"1347–Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1302–1365":"1302–1365","1302–1320":"1302–1320","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1354":"1354","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1354–":"1354–Décédée","1347–Female":"1347–Décédée","1354–Female":"1354–Décédée","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1302–1365":"1302–1365","1302–1320":"1302–1320","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1354":"1354","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Joan ferch Owain of Abergavenny est née en 1354, à Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Galles, son père, Owain Ap Caradoc, avait 52 ans et sa mère, Lleucu Gwyn ferch Einion Sais, avait 52 ans. Elle a épousé John Jenkin. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1354–":"1354–Verstorben","1347–Female":"1347–Verstorben","1354–Female":"1354–Verstorben","1350–Male":"1350–Verstorben","1360–Female":"1360–Verstorben","1302–1365":"1302–136